100 Years Ago Today, This is What Was Happening ...

On February 16, 1926, the United States Senate voted to approve the Johnson Act, aimed at limiting immigration from certain countries, sparking heated debate over national identity and economic impact. In Europe, the British government faced mounting pressure amid ongoing strikes, as workers demanded better wages and conditions. Meanwhile, in Germany, the political landscape grew more precarious as the rise of extremist groups threatened stability.
